ssive excitatory neurotransmission alone","Desynchronised neuronal firing patterns","Primary brainstem dysfunction","Thalamocortical circuit involvement in generalised seizures","Excessive inhibitory neurotransmission alone"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe pathophysiology of epilepsy involves complex interactions between brain regions. \u003Cstrong\u003EThalamocortical circuit involvement in generalised seizures\u003C/strong\u003E is a key mechanism, particularly in generalised epilepsy syndromes where these circuits contribute to the generation and propagation of seizure activity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcessive excitatory neurotransmission alone\u003C/strong\u003E - Epilepsy involves an imbalance between both excitatory and inhibitory neurotransmission\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDesynchronised neuronal firing patterns\u003C/strong\u003E - Epileptic seizures are characterised by hypersynchronous (not desynchronised) neuronal firing\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary brainstem dysfunction\u003C/strong\u003E - Most epileptic seizures originate in the cerebral cortex, not the brainstem\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcessive inhibitory neurotransmission alone\u003C/strong\u003E - Like the first option, this oversimplifies the complex interplay between excitatory and inhibitory mechanisms\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe generation of epileptic seizures typically involves both cortical hyperexcitability and hypersynchrony, with important contributions from subcortical structures in generalised epilepsy syndromes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Epilepsy involves an imbalance between excitatory and inhibitory neurotransmission in the brain.","Generalised epilepsies involve interactions between cortical and subcortical structures, particularly thalamocortical circuits.","Epileptic seizures are characterised by hypersynchronous neuronal discharges."],"references":["Kammerman S, Wasserman L. Seizure disorders: Part 1. Classification and diagnosis. West J Med. 2001 Aug;175(2):99-103. doi: 10.1136/ewjm.175.2.99. PMID: 11483551; PMCID: PMC1071497","Fisher RS, Cross JH, French JA, Higurashi N, Hirsch E, Jansen FE, Lagae L, Mosh\u00e9 SL, Peltola J, Roulet Perez E, Scheffer IE, Zuberi SM. Operational classification of seizure types by the International League Against Epilepsy: Position Paper of the ILAE Commission for Classification and Terminology. Epilepsia. 2017 Apr;58(4):522-530. doi: 10.1111/epi.13670. Epub 2017 Mar 8. PMID: 28276060","Sarmast ST, Abdullahi AM, Jahan N. Current Classification of Seizures and Epilepsies: Scope, Limitations and Recommendations for Future Action. Cureus. 2020 Sep 20;12(9):e10549. doi: 10.7759/cureus.10549. PMID: 33101797; PMCID: PMC7575300","Huff JS, Murr NI. Seizure. 2023 Feb 7. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28613516","Tenney JR, Glauser TA. The current state of absence epilepsy: can we have your attention? Epilepsy Curr. 2013 May;13(3):135-40. doi: 10.5698/1535-7511-13.3.135. PMID: 23840175; PMCID: PMC3697883"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60622"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16453"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60622","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60622"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T22:51:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T22:55:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9144"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75114"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"descriptio